Summary

1. OpenShift Routes (External Access to Applications)
In Kubernetes, services are internal only by default.
To allow external users (internet or corporate network) to access an application, OpenShift uses Routes.
A Route exposes a service with a hostname.
Example:
https://www.example.com
Architecture:
User
  │
  ▼
OpenShift Router
  │
  ▼
Route
  │
  ▼
Service
  │
  ▼
Pod
Command to create a route:
oc create route edge myroute --service=myservice
This exposes the service externally.
________________________________________
2. Route Hostname
Each route is accessible via a hostname.
Example:
product.apps.ocp4.example.com
Where:
Part	Meaning
product	application
apps	router domain
ocp4.example.com	cluster domain
Example command:
oc expose service product
This automatically creates a route.
Check routes:
oc get routes
________________________________________
3. Types of Route Encryption
OpenShift supports 3 TLS encryption methods.
________________________________________
1️⃣ Edge TLS
TLS connection ends at the OpenShift router.
Flow:
Client
   │ HTTPS
   ▼
Router
   │ HTTP
   ▼
Pod
Characteristics:
Feature	Description
TLS termination	Router
Internal traffic	HTTP
Security	Moderate
Example:
oc create route edge myroute \
--service=myservice \
--hostname=www.example.com
________________________________________
2️⃣ Passthrough TLS
Router does not decrypt TLS.
Flow:
Client
   │ HTTPS
   ▼
Router
   │ HTTPS
   ▼
Pod
Characteristics:
Feature	Description
TLS termination	Pod
Router inspection	Not possible
Security	High
Example:
oc create route passthrough myroute \
--service=myservice
________________________________________
3️⃣ Re-encryption TLS
TLS ends at router and then re-encrypted again.
Flow:
Client
   │ HTTPS
   ▼
Router
   │ HTTPS
   ▼
Pod
But router decrypts and re-encrypts.
Characteristics:
Feature	Description
TLS termination	Router
Re-encrypted	Yes
Security	Very High
Example:
oc create route reencrypt myroute \
--service=myservice
________________________________________
4. Certificates for Routes
Secure routes require TLS certificates.
Certificates must include:
File	Purpose
certificate	public certificate
private key	private key
CA certificate	certificate authority
Example command:
oc create route edge myroute \
--service=myservice \
--cert=mycert.pem \
--key=mykey.pem \
--hostname=www.example.com
Certificates must be signed by trusted CA.
Examples of CA:
•	Corporate CA
•	Let's Encrypt
•	DigiCert
•	GlobalSign
________________________________________
5. Default Cluster Networking Behavior
In OpenShift, all pods can talk to all other pods by default.
Default network rule:
Allow all traffic
Example:
Pod A  ---> Pod B  (Allowed)
Pod B  ---> Pod C  (Allowed)
This is not secure for production.
________________________________________
6. Network Policies (Pod Firewall)
To restrict pod communication, OpenShift uses NetworkPolicy.
NetworkPolicy works like a firewall for pods.
Example:
Allow only product → stock
Block everything else
________________________________________
NetworkPolicy uses labels
Instead of IP addresses.
Example:
podSelector:
  matchLabels:
    app: stock
Allow traffic from:
from:
- podSelector:
    matchLabels:
      app: product
Example NetworkPolicy:
apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: NetworkPolicy
metadata:
  name: stock-policy
spec:
  podSelector:
    matchLabels:
      app: stock
  ingress:
  - from:
    - podSelector:
        matchLabels:
          app: product
Apply policy:
oc apply -f policy.yaml
________________________________________
7. Logical Network Zones
Network policies allow creating logical network zones.
Example corporate architecture:
Frontend Zone
Backend Zone
Database Zone
Example:
Frontend pods → Backend pods
Backend pods → Database pods
Database pods → No external access
Network policies enforce these rules.
________________________________________
8. OpenShift Service CA Controller
OpenShift has a built-in certificate authority.
Component:
service-ca controller
Purpose:
Automatically generate TLS certificates for services.
________________________________________
9. Automatic Service Certificate Creation
To request a certificate for a service, add annotation:
service.beta.openshift.io/serving-cert-secret-name=my-secret
Example service:
apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: myservice
  annotations:
    service.beta.openshift.io/serving-cert-secret-name: my-secret
OpenShift automatically creates:
Secret: my-secret
Contents:
File	Purpose
tls.crt	certificate
tls.key	private key
________________________________________
10. Service Certificate Hostnames
Generated certificate includes service DNS names:
Example:
service.namespace.svc
service.namespace.svc.cluster.local
Example:
stock.network-review.svc
This allows secure internal communication.
________________________________________
11. Injecting CA Certificates into ConfigMaps
Clients must trust the service certificate.
OpenShift allows injecting CA certificate into a ConfigMap.
Add annotation:
service.beta.openshift.io/inject-cabundle=true
Example ConfigMap:
apiVersion: v1
kind: ConfigMap
metadata:
  name: service-ca
  annotations:
    service.beta.openshift.io/inject-cabundle: "true"
OpenShift adds:
service-ca.crt
________________________________________
12. Client Applications Use CA Bundle
Client pods mount the ConfigMap.
Example:
volumeMounts:
- mountPath: /etc/pki/ca-trust/extracted/pem
  name: trusted-ca
Volume:
volumes:
- name: trusted-ca
  configMap:
    name: service-ca
Now clients trust service certificates.
________________________________________
13. Service Certificate Rotation
Certificates eventually expire.
To rotate certificate manually:
Delete the secret.
Example:
oc delete secret my-secret
The service-ca controller automatically generates a new certificate.
________________________________________
14. Security Workflow Summary
Internal TLS flow:
Service Annotation
        │
        ▼
Service CA Controller
        │
        ▼
Secret Created
        │
        ▼
Pod mounts secret
        │
        ▼
Service runs HTTPS
        │
        ▼
CA injected into ConfigMap
        │
        ▼
Client trusts certificate
________________________________________
